-Catholic Church in United Kingdom\n|\n|-\n| St Barnabas Church, [[Old Heath]]\n| [[Colchester]]\n| Very high Church of England. Eastward-facing orientation of the priest at the altar; unleavened bread for the Eucharist; incense and candles; statue of the Blessed Virgin Mary with votive lights; holy water stoup at the entrance; Confession available on request. [[Book of Common Prayer]] used daily for the [[Morning Prayer (Anglican)|Morning]] and [[Evening Prayer (Anglican)|Evening]] Prayer and also for Mass once a week. Self - identifies as Anglo-Catholic.\n|\n|-\n|St Oswald's Church, \n[[Tile Hill]]\n|[[Coventry]]\n|Self-identifies as Anglo-Catholic.  Use of candles and thurible for incense; statue of the Blessed Virgin Mary with votive lights; holy water stoup at the entrance; Stations of the Cross; representations of the Seven Sacraments; prayers for the dead; sung Mass; annual pilgrimage to [[Walsingham]].\n|Dedicated in June 1957, the church was designed by [[Basil Spence]], who was also responsible for the contemporaneous [[Coventry Cathedral#Present structure|Coventry Cathedral]] (dedicated 1962).  St Oswald's was given Grade 2 [[Listed building]] status in 2014.\n|-\n|[[Church of St James the Great, Darlington|St James the Great]]\n| [[Darlington]]\n| Self-identifies as Anglo-Catholic.\n|\n|-\n|Saint Salvador's Church\n|[[Dundee]]\n|Self-identifies as Anglo-Catholic; Rector is [[Society_of_the_Holy_Cross|SSC ]] member; Website states many members are sympathetic to [[Forward in Faith]] and that congregation is conservative catholic. \n|-\n|[[Church of St Michael and All Saints, Edinburgh|St. Michael and All Saints]]\n|[[Edinburgh]]\n|Self-identifies as Anglo-Catholic with Sunday Solemn Mass with East Facing celebrations; Daily Low Mass except Monday, weekly confessions, weekly Rosary, weekly Benediction.  Incense and traditional language is used.|\n|\n|-\n|[[Old Saint Paul's, Edinburgh|Old Saint Paul's]]\n| [[Edinburgh]]\n| Self-identifies as Anglo-Catholic.