]] (USA) (1990\u2013 ) Women\u2019s Pipeline Championship winner\n*[[Jimmy Blears]] (1948\u20132011) (Haw) 1972 World Champion<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.worldchampionsofsurfing.com/jimmy-blears-biography/ | title = Jimmy Blears \u2013 Biography | accessdate = April 23, 2012 | work = World Champions of Surfing | url-status = dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20131214102841/http://www.worldchampionsofsurfing.com/jimmy-blears-biography/ | archivedate = December 14, 2013 }}</ref>\n*[[Wendy Botha]] (1965\u2013 ) (Aus) Four-time world surfing champion\n*[[Lynne Boyer]] (1956\u2013 ) (USA) Two-time world surfing champion 1978 & 1979\n*[[Ken Bradshaw]] (1952\u2013 ) (USA) North Shore hellman\n*[[Scott Brill]] (1966\u2013 ) (USA) Daytona Beach. Progressive Shortboarder and Aerialist.   \n*[[Bruce Brown]] (1937\u20132017) San Francisco. Surfing film maker\n*[[Chris Brown (surfer)|Chris Brown]] (1970-2019) Carpinteria, California. \n*[[Bud Browne]] (1912\u20132008) (USA) Pioneer surf film maker, the first filmmaker to show surf movies commercially\n*[[Pam Burridge]] (1965\u2013 ) (Aus) 1990 women's world champion<ref>{{cite web|last1=Carroll|first1=Nick|title=Pam Burridge (July 26, 1965-)|url=http://www.surfline.com/surfing-a-to-z/pam-burridge-biography-and-photos_773/|website=Surfing A to Z|publisher=Surfline|accessdate=24 October 2014}}</ref>\n*[[Taj Burrow]] (1978\u2013 ) (Aus) 1998 ASP World Tour Rookie of the Year, many ASP Tour wins\n\n== C ==\n*[[Ian Cairns]] (1952\u2013 ) (Aus) Champion surfer in the late 1970s\n*[[Corky Carroll]] (1947\u2013 ) Five Time U.S. Champion, 3 Time International Professional Champion, International Big Wave Champion, World Small Wave Champion\n*[[Richie Collins (surfer)|Richie Collins]] (1969\u2013 ) (USA)(surfer/shaper) Won 1988 O'Neil Coldwater Classic, 1989 Op Pro, 1992 Bells Beach Classic\n*[[Heather Clark (surfer)|Heather Clark]] (RSA) 2001 Hawaiian Triple Crown champion\n*Cas Collier (RSA) 1999 World Big Wave Champion<ref>{{cite web|title=Cas Collier|url=http://whoswho.co.za/cas-collier-8021|website=Who's Who of Southern Africa|accessdate=24 October 2014}}</ref>\n*[[Aaron \"Gorkin\" Cormican]] (USA) (1979- ) Surfer/Shaper.  Four Time ECSC Surfing Champion.  Aerial Pioneer.  Known for the \"Gorkin Flip\"\n\n== D ==\n*Mike Diffenderfer (1937\u20132002) (USA) Surfer and shaper<ref>{{cite news|last1=Gordon|first1=Mike|title=Mike Diffenderfer, surfboard shaper, dead at 64|url=http://the.honoluluadvertiser.com/article/2002/May/23/ln/ln60a.html|accessdate=17 September 2014|work=[[The Honolulu Advertiser]]|date=23 May 2002}}</ref>\n*[[Miki Dora]] (1936\u20132002) (USA) <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.surfline.com/surfaz/dora_miki.cfm |title=Miki Dora Biography and Photos |publisher=Surfline.Com |date=January 3, 2002 |accessdate=July 20, 2012}}</ref>\n*[[Shane Dorian]], (Haw) Pro surfer\n*Mike Doyle (1941\u2013 2019 ) (USA) Surf/paddle champion, innovator. 1965 World Champion. Winner, 1968 Duke Kahanamoku Contest.<ref>http://www.ocregister.com/articles/surfing-231510-mike-one.html</ref>\n\n== E ==\n*[[Laura Enever]] (1991\u2013 ) (Aus) 2009 ASP Women\u2019s World Junior Champion<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.aspworldtour.com/surfers/womens-profiles/laura-enever/ | title = Surfer Profile: Laura Enever | accessdate = November 4, 2011 | work = aspworldtour.com | publisher = Association of Surfing Professionals}}</ref>\n*[[Michael Eppelstun]] (Aus) 1994 bodyboarding world champion\n\n== F ==\n*[[Mick Fanning]] (Aus) (2002\u20132018) 3x World Champion\n*[[Midget Farrelly]] (Aus) (1944\u20132016) Won the inaugural World Surfing Championship in 1964\n*[[Sally Fitzgibbons]] (Aus) (1990\u2013 ) Multi ASP World Tour title-holder\n*[[John John Florence]] (Haw) (1992\u2013 ) Won the 2011 Vans World Cup of Surfing, the youngest winner\n*[[Jeremy Flores]] (1988\u2013 ) (Fra) 2007 WCT Rookie of the Year\n*[[Mark Foo]] (1958\u20131994) (Haw) Professional surfer. Died while surfing at Mavericks.\n*[[Donavon Frankenreiter]] (1972\u2013 ) (USA) Surfer and musician\n*[[George Freeth]] (Haw) (1883\u20131919) \"The Father of Modern Surfing\"\n*[[Skip Frye]] (1941\u2013 ) (USA) Legendary stylist and surfboard shaper\n*[[Jim Fuller (musician)|Jim Fuller]] Godfather of surf guitar, [[Surfaris]]\n\n== G ==\n*[[Nick Gabaldon]] (1927\u20131951) California's first documented surfer of Black and Hispanic descent\n*[[Maya Gabeira]] (1987\u2013 ) (Bra) Surfed the biggest wave ever by a female at {{convert|45|ft|m}}\n*[[Sunny Garcia]] (1970\u2013 ) (Haw) 2000 World Champion\n*[[Yasnyiar Bonne Gea]] (1982\u2013 ) Indonesian surfing champion<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.driftsurfing.eu/exclusive-behind-the-scenes-nias-point-of-change/|title=EXCLUSIVE BEHIND THE SCENES: Nias - Point Of Change - Drift Surfing|date=2015-01-09|language=en-GB|access-date=2016-08-24}}</ref>\n*[[Stephanie Gilmore]] (1988\u2013 ) (Aus) 2007 ASP World Champion\n*[[George Greenough]] (1941\u2013 ) (USA/Aus) 1960s [[kneeboard]], shortboard, inventor and [[surf movie]]s.\n\n== H ==\n*[[Jeff Hakman]] (1948\u2013 ) (Haw) Surfing champion of the 1970s\n*[[Bethany Hamilton]] (February 8, 1990\u2013 ), (USA) Victim of a much-publicised [[shark]] attack.\n*[[Laird Hamilton]] (March 2, 1964\u2013 ), (USA) (Hawaii and California), Big wave rider and tow-in surfing inventor.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.surfline.com/surfaz/hamilton_laird.cfm |title=Laird Hamilton Biography and Photos |publisher=Surfline.Com |date= |accessdate=July 20, 2012}}</ref>\n*Damian Hardman (1966\u2013 ) (Aus) 1987 & 1991 World Champion<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.worldchampionsofsurfing.com/damien-hardman-biography/ | title = Damien Hardman \u2013 Biography | accessdate = April 23, 2012 | work = World Champions of Surfing | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20110507083024/http://www.worldchampionsofsurfing.com/damien-hardman-biography/ | archive-date = May 7, 2011 | url-status = dead }}</ref>\n*[[Paige Hareb]] (NZ)\n*[[Peter Harris (surfer)|Peter Harris]] (1958\u2013 ) (Aus) Won the 1980 [[Stubbies (surfing)|Stubbies]] as a rookie\n*[[Chelsea Hedges]] (1983\u2013 ) (Aus) 2005 world title holder\n*[[Fred Hemmings]] (Haw) 1968 World Champion\n*[[Michael (Mick) Hickey]], (1937\u20132015), Australian, European (French) surfing champion, Biarritz 1962, Pipeline pioneer\n*[[Coco Ho]] (1991\u2013 ) (Haw) Women's ASP World Tour surfer, Michael Ho's daughter\n*[[Derek Ho]] (Haw) 1993 World Champion, Michael Ho's younger son\n*[[Michael Ho (surfer)|Michael Ho]] (1957\u2013 ) (Haw) Won Hawaiian Triple Crown, Duke Classic, World Cup and 1982 Pipe Masters\n*[[CJ Hobgood]] (1979\u2013 ) (USA) 2001 World Champion\n*[[Damien Hobgood]] (USA)\n*[[Joyce Hoffman (surfer)|Joyce Hoffman]] (USA) US Women's Champion 1965\u201367\n*[[Philip Hoffman (surfing)|Phillip Hoffman]] (1930\u20132010) American big wave pioneer and surf apparel company executive<ref>{{cite news |title= Philip 'Flippy' Hoffman dies at 80; big-wave pioneer co-owned surfwear-related fabric company |date= November 16, 2010 |author= Dennis McLellan |newspaper= [[Los Angeles Times]] |url= http://www.latimes.com/news/obituaries/la-me-philip-hoffman-20101116,0,7837924.story |accessdate= November 23, 2010 }}</ref>\n*Cheyne Horan (Aus) Active 1975-1993, world championship runner-up four times<ref>{{cite news|last1=Elliott|first1=Tim|title=After the wave has broken|url=http://www.smh.com.au/sport/after-the-wave-has-broken-20120111-1pv7q.html|accessdate=21 May 2016|work=[[Sydney Morning Herald]]|date=12 January 2012}}</ref>\n*[[Jeff Hubbard]] (1975\u2013 ) (Haw) 3-time World Bodyboarding Champion\n*Mike Hynson (USA) Star of [[The Endless Summer]] and surf board shaper who taught Robert August how to shape<ref>{{cite news | first = Nick | last = Schou | title = Mike Hynson star of 'The Endless Summer,' resurfaces with tales of the Brotherhood | date = Jul 9, 2009 | url = http://www.ocweekly.com/2009-07-09/news/mike-hynson-the-endless-summer-the-brotherhood/ | work = OC Weekly | accessdate = June 13, 2012}}</ref>\n\n== I ==\n*[[Andy Irons]] (1978\u20132010) (Haw) Three-time world champion 2002\u20132004\n*[[Bruce Irons (surfer)|Bruce Irons]] (Haw)\n\n==J==\n*[[John Holeman]], professional surfer of the 1980s and 1990s\n*[[Jay Moriarity]], professional surfer of Santa Cruz, 1978-2001\n\n== K ==\n*[[Duke Paoa Kahanamoku]] (August 24, 1890 \u2013 January 22, 1968), (Haw) US Olympic Swimming Champion, Hawaiian Personality. The Father of Modern Surfing. Made appearances in Hollywood films (Mr. Roberts with Henry Fonda and Wake of the Red Witch with John Wayne).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.surfline.com/surfaz/kahanamoku_duke.cfm |title=Duke Kahanamoku Biography and Photos |publisher=Surfline.Com |date=January 22, 1968 |accessdate=July 20, 2012}}</ref>\n*[[Dave Kalama]] (1964\u2013 ) (Haw) windsurfing and paddleboard champion\n*Drew Kampion (1944\u2013 ) (USA) surf writer and editor, editor of Surfer Magazine (1968\u201371), author of Stoked: A History of Surf Culture, The Way of the Surfer, The Book of Waves, etc.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.pnwlocalnews.com/news/25485859.html |title=Drew Kampion of Whidbey Island will be placed on Surfing Walk of Fame |publisher=PNWLocalNews |date=July 15, 2008 |accessdate=July 20, 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141025023521/http://www.pnwlocalnews.com/news/25485859.html |archive-date=October 25, 2014 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n*[[Keala Kennelly]] (1978\u2013 ) (USA)\n*[[Damian King]] (Aus) 2003 & 2004 World Bodyboarding Champion\n\n== L ==\n*[[Randy Laine|Wes Laine]] (1960\u2013 ) A top 10 ASP World Championship Tour competitor - Wins: 1984 World Cup Sunset Beach, 1983 OP-Pro Atlantic City, 1985 Spur Ranch, Cape Town, South Africa, 2nd Place 1983 Rip-Curl Pro, Bells Beach<ref>[http://www.aspworldtour.com/pdf/men_eventchamps.pdf Wes Laine ASP] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120617065128/http://www.aspworldtour.com/pdf/men_eventchamps.pdf |date=2012-06-17 }}</ref>\n*[[Isabel Letham]] (1899\u20131995) (Aus) First Australian to surf.\n*[[Antony Garrett Lisi]] (USA) Physicist.\n*[[Jack London]] (1876\u20131916) (USA) Writer, Hawaiian surfer\n*[[Gerry Lopez]] (1948\u2013 ), (Haw) \"Mr.Pipeline\", Founder of Lightning Bolt surfboards and Actor (played role of Subotai in ''[[Conan the Barbarian (1982 film)|Conan the Barbarian]]'')<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.surfline.com/surfaz/lopez_gerry.cfm |title=Gerry Lopez Biography and Photos |publisher=Surfline.Com |date=November 7, 1948 |accessdate=July 20, 2012}}</ref>\n*[[Barton Lynch]] (1963\u2013 ) (Aus) 1988 World Champion, won 17 world tour events<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.surfline.com/surfing-a-to-z/barton-lynch-biography-and-photos_853/ | title = Barton Lynch (August 9, 1963\u2013) | accessdate = February 23, 2012 | last = MacDonald| first = Tim | date = Oct 2000 | work = Surfing A to Z | publisher = Surfline}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.worldchampionsofsurfing.com/barton-lynch-biography/ | title = Barton Lynch \u2013 Biography | accessdate = February 23, 2012 | work = World Champions of Surfing \u2013 A Virtual Surf Museum | publisher = IDW Publishing | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20110312003821/http://www.worldchampionsofsurfing.com/barton-lynch-biography/ | archive-date = March 12, 2011 | url-status = dead }}</ref>\n*[[Wayne Lynch]] (1952\u2013 ) (Aus) <ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.surfresearch.com.au/sLynch_Wayne.html| title = Wayne Lynch biography|publisher = SurfResearch.com}}</ref> Influential Australian goofy-foot and winner of numerous 1960s and 1970s surf contests; subject of the 2013 biographical documentary ''Uncharted Waters''<ref>{{cite web | url = http://unchartedwaters.com.au | title = Uncharted Waters Documentary official website}}</ref>\n\n== M ==\n*[[Rob Machado]] (1973\u2013 ) (USA) Won Pipeline Masters and U.S. Open of Surfing\n*[[Cheyne Magnusson]] (c. 1984), US\n*[[Ishita Malaviya]], (India) First Indian female surfer\n*[[Malia Manuel]] (1993\u2013 ) (Haw) 2008 US Open Champion (youngest ever)<ref>{{cite news | first = Travis | last = Ferr\u00e9 | title = Defending Champ at 15 | date = July 17, 2009 | url = http://www.surfingmagazine.com/news/defending-champ-at-15/ | work = Surfing Magazine | accessdate = June 13, 2012}}</ref>\n*[[Bobby Martinez]] (1986\u2013 ) (USA) 2006 Rookie of the Year\n*[[Clay Marzo]] (1989\u2013 ) (USA) Three NSSA National surfing titles, a nomination for Maneuver of the Year at the 2007 Surfer Magazine Poll and Video Awards\n*[[Gabriel Medina]] (1993\u2013 ) (BRA) 2013 WSL World Junior Champion, 2014 WSL World Champion (first Brazilian to win the title), 2015 Vans Triple Crown of Surfing Champion\n*[[Pauline Menczer]] (1970\u2013 ) (Aus) 1988 amateur world champion, 1993 world champion \n*[[Jessi Miley-Dyer]] (1986\u2013 ) (Aus)\n*Wayne Miyata (1942\u20132005) (USA) California and Hawaii, \"going tubular\" in Endless Summer, famous color glosser<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.surfwriter.net/waynes_tribute.htm | title = Wayne Miyata dead at 63 | accessdate = November 4, 2011 | last = Feigel | first = Robert R. | year = 2001 | work = Surfwriter}}</ref>\n*[[Carissa Moore]] (1992\u2013 ) (Haw) 2011 ASP Women's World Champion, youngest female ever to win\n*[[Jay Moriarity]] (1978\u20132001) (USA)\n*[[Sof\u00eda Mul\u00e1novich]] (1983\u2013 ) (Peru) First South American to win the World Title in 2004\n*[[Mickey Munoz|Mickey Mu\u00f1oz]] (1937\u2013 ) (USA) Early surfing pioneer, also famous as a surfboard shaper\n\n== N ==\n*[[Greg Noll]] (1937\u2013 ) (USA) Big wave pioneer, rode biggest wave of his era at Makaha\n*[[Kem Nunn]] (USA) Avid surfer and America's leading surf novelist\n*[[David Nuuhiwa]] (1948\u2013 ) (USA) legendary nose rider from the 1960s\n\n== O ==\n\n*[[Margo Oberg]] (1953\u2013 ) (Haw) Three-time world champion 1977, 1980 & 1981\n*[[Jamie O'Brien (surfer)|Jamie O'Brien]] (1983\u2013 ) (Haw) Won ASP Pipeline Masters as a wildcard\n*[[Mark Occhilupo]] (1966\u2013 ) (Aus) 1999 world champion\n*[[Phyllis O'Donnell]] (1937\u2013 ) (Aus) In 1964 won the inaugural women's World Championship Surfing Title at Manly Beach\n*[[Jack O'Neill (businessman)|Jack O'Neill]] (1923\u20132017) Surfer and inventor of the modern wetsuit\n\n== P ==\n*[[Joel Parkinson]] (1981\u2013 ) (Aus)\n*[[Mike Parsons (surfer)|Mike Parsons]] (1965\u2013 ) Surfed largest recorded wave of {{convert|70|ft|m|abbr=on}} at [[Cortes Bank]]\n*[[Stacey Peralta]] (1957\u2013 ) (USA) Z-Boy\n*[[Lakey Peterson]] (1994\u2013 ) (USA)\n*[[Michael Peterson (surfer)|Michael Peterson]] (1952\u20132012) (Aus) Australian champion 1972 & 1974\n*[[Bob Pike (surfer)|Bob Pike]] (1940\u20131999) (Aus) Noted [[big wave surfing|big wave surfer]]\n*Felipe Pomar (1943\u2013 ) (Peru) 1965 World Champion<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.worldchampionsofsurfing.com/felipe-pomar-biography/ | title = Felipe Pomar \u2013 World Champion Tsunami Rider | accessdate = May 23, 2013 | work = World Champions of Surfing \u2013 A Virtual Surf Museum | publisher = IDW Publishing | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20120628025550/http://www.worldchampionsofsurfing.com/felipe-pomar-biography/ | archive-date = June 28, 2012 | url-status = dead }}</ref>\n*[[Martin Potter (surfer)|Martin Potter]] (1965\u2013 ) (RSA) 1989 World Champion\n\n== Q ==\n*[[Maz Quinn]] (1976\u2013 ) (NZ) 4-time NZ national champion\n\n== R ==\n*[[Mark Richards (surfer)|Mark Richards]] (1957\u2013 ) (Aus) 4-time World Champion 1979\u20131982\n\n==S==\n*[[Jacqueline Silva]] (1979\u2013 ) (Bra) Pioneer in Brazilian women's surfing\n*[[Robert Wilson Simmons|Bob Simmons]] (1919\u20131954) (USA) Father of the modern surfboard\n*[[Kelly Slater]] (1972\u2013 ) (USA) 11-time World Champion\n*[[Jordy Smith]] (1988\u2013 ) (RSA)\n*[[Mike Stewart (bodyboarder)|Mike Stewart]] (1963\u2013 ) (Haw) 9-time World Bodyboarding Champion\n*[[Rell Sunn]] (1950\u20131998) (Haw) A top female surfer 