) 2013 WSL World Junior Champion, 2014 WSL World Champion (first Brazilian to win the title), 2015 Vans Triple Crown of Surfing Champion\n*[[Pauline Menczer]] (1970\u2013 ) (Aus) 1988 amateur world champion, 1993 world champion \n*[[Jessi Miley-Dyer]] (1986\u2013 ) (Aus)\n*Wayne Miyata (1942\u20132005) (USA) California and Hawaii, \"going tubular\" in Endless Summer, famous color glosser<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.surfwriter.net/waynes_tribute.htm | title = Wayne Miyata dead at 63 | accessdate = November 4, 2011 | last = Feigel | first = Robert R. | year = 2001 | work = Surfwriter}}</ref>\n*[[Carissa Moore]] (1992\u2013 ) (Haw) 2011 ASP Women's World Champion, youngest female ever to win\n*[[Jay Moriarity]] (1978\u20132001) (USA)\n*[[Sof\u00eda Mul\u00e1novich]] (1983\u2013 ) (Peru) First South American to win the World Title in 2004\n*[[Mickey Munoz|Mickey Mu\u00f1oz]] (1937\u2013 ) (USA) Early surfing pioneer, also famous as a surfboard shaper\n\n== N ==\n*[[Greg Noll]] (1937\u2013 ) (USA) Big wave pioneer, rode biggest wave of his era at Makaha\n*[[Kem Nunn]] (USA) Avid surfer and America's leading surf novelist\n*[[David Nuuhiwa]] (1948\u2013 ) (USA) legendary nose rider from the 1960s\n\n== O ==\n\n*[[Margo Oberg]] (1953\u2013 ) (Haw) Three-time world champion 1977, 1980 & 1981\n*[[Jamie O'Brien (surfer)|Jamie O'Brien]] (1983\u2013 ) (Haw) Won ASP Pipeline Masters as a wildcard\n*[[Mark Occhilupo]] (1966\u2013 ) (Aus) 1999 world champion\n*[[Phyllis O'Donnell]] (1937\u2013 ) (Aus) In 1964 won the inaugural women's World Championship Surfing Title at Manly Beach\n*[[Jack O'Neill (businessman)|Jack O'Neill]] (1923\u20132017) Surfer and inventor of the modern wetsuit\n\n== P ==\n*[[Joel Parkinson]] (1981\u2013 ) (Aus)\n*[[Mike Parsons (surfer)|Mike Parsons]] (1965\u2013 ) Surfed largest recorded wave of {{convert|70|ft|m|abbr=on}} at [[Cortes Bank]]\n*[[Stacey Peralta]] (1957\u2013 ) (USA) Z-Boy\n*[[Lakey Peterson]] (1994\u2013 ) (USA)\n*[[Michael Peterson (surfer)|Michael Peterson]] (1952\u20132012) (Aus) Australian champion 1972 & 1974\n*[[Bob Pike (surfer)|Bob Pike]] (1940\u20131999) (Aus) Noted [[big wave surfing|big wave surfer]]\n*Felipe Pomar (1943\u2013 ) (Peru) 1965 World Champion<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.worldchampionsofsurfing.com/felipe-pomar-biography/ | title = Felipe Pomar \u2013 World Champion Tsunami Rider | accessdate = May 23, 2013 | work = World Champions of Surfing \u2013 A Virtual Surf Museum | publisher = IDW Publishing | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20120628025550/http://www.worldchampionsofsurfing.com/felipe-pomar-biography/ | archive-date = June 28, 2012 | url-status = dead }}</ref>\n*[[Martin Potter (surfer)|Martin Potter]] (1965\u2013 ) (RSA) 1989 World Champion\n\n== Q ==\n*[[Maz Quinn]] (1976\u2013 ) (NZ) 4-time NZ national champion\n\n== R ==\n*[[Mark Richards (surfer)|Mark Richards]] (1957\u2013 ) (Aus) 4-time World Champion 1979\u20131982\n\n==S==\n*[[Jacqueline Silva]] (1979\u2013 ) (Bra) Pioneer in Brazilian women's surfing\n*[[Robert Wilson Simmons|Bob Simmons]] (1919\u20131954) (USA) Father of the modern surfboard\n*[[Kelly Slater]] (1972\u2013 ) (USA) 11-time World Champion\n*[[Jordy Smith]] (1988\u2013 ) (RSA)\n*[[Mike Stewart (bodyboarder)|Mike Stewart]] (1963\u2013 ) (Haw) 9-time World Bodyboarding Champion\n*[[Rell Sunn]] (1950\u20131998) (Haw) A top female surfer of the 1980s, known as the \"Queen of Makaha\"\n\n== T ==\n*[[Donald Takayama]] (1943\u20132012) (USA) [[U.S. Open of Surfing|Master's division of the United States Surfing Champions]] 1971, 1972 and 1973\n*[[Guilherme Tamega]] (Bra) 6-time world champion bodyboarder\n*[[Shaun Tomson]] (1955\u2013 ) (USA) Born in South Africa, currently living in the USA, 1977 World Champion\n*[[Peter Townend (surfer)|Peter Townend]] (1953\u2013 ) (Aus) 1976 World Champion\n*[[Buzzy Trent]] (1929\u20132006) (USA) Pioneer of big wave surfing<ref>{{cite news|title=Buzzy Trent: RIP Makaha's big wave charger dies at 77|url=http://www.surfline.com/surfnews/article.cfm?id=4460|accessdate=24 October 2014|work=Surfline|publisher=Surfline/Wavetrak, Inc.}}</ref>\n*[[Joel Tudor]] (1976\u2013 ) (USA) Famous contemporary longboarder\n\n== V ==\n*[[Butch Van Artsdalen]] (1941\u20131979) (Haw) the original Mr. Pipeline\n*[[Dale Velzy]] (1927\u20132005) (USA) 1950s surf shop pioneer and surfboard design innovator<ref>{{cite news | first = Margalit | last = Fox | title = Dale Velzy, 77, a pioneer in popularizing surfing, dies | date = June 5, 2005 | url = https://www.nytimes.com/2005/06/05/sports/othersports/05VELZY.html | work = The New York Times | accessdate = June 13, 2012}}</ref>\n*[[Peter Viertel]] (1920\u20132007) (USA) Introduced surfing in Europe \n*[[Mark Visser]] (1983\u2013 ) (Aus) Big-wave surfer, the \"Night Rider\"\n\n== W ==\n*[[Robert \"Wingnut\" Weaver]] Featured, along with Patrick O'Connell, in The Endless Summer II surf film.\n*[[Sharon Webber]] (USA)  Women's world surfing championship in 1970 & 1972\n*[[Dewey Weber]] (1938\u20131993) (USA) Surfer and surfboard designer\n*[[Dale Webster]] (1948\u2013 ) (USA) Northern California surfer who surfed over 10,407 days in a row, minimum of 3 waves a day. Appeared in the [[Step Into Liquid]] movie.\n*[[John Whitmore (surfer)|John Whitmore]] (RSA) South African surfing pioneer.\n*[[Dennis Wilson]] (1944\u20131983) (USA) Founding member of [[The Beach Boys]]\n*[[Owen Wright]] (1990\u2013 ) (Aus)  Won 2011 Quiksilver Pro<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.surfermag.com/features/owen-wright-wins-in-new-york/ | title = Owen Wright wins at New York | accessdate = June 13, 2012 | last = Thompson | first = Brendan | date = Sep 9, 2011 | work = Surfer Magazine}}</ref>\n*[[Tyler Wright (surfer)|Tyler Wright]] (1994\u2013 ) (Aus) 2016 WSL Women's World Champion<ref>{{cite news | first = Amanda | last = Lulham | title = Owen and Tyler Wright clean up at Surfing Australia Awards | date = February 17, 2012 | url = http://www.dailytelegraph.com.au/sport/more-sports/owen-and-tyler-wright-clean-up-at-surfing-australia-awards/story-e6frey6i-1226273139822 | work = The Daily Telegragh | accessdate = June 13, 2012}}</ref>\n\n== Y ==\n*[[Nat Young (surfer)|Nat Young]] (1947\u2013 ) (Aus) World surfing champion 1966 & 1970, ASP World Longboard Tour Champion 1986 & 1988\u20131990. Tried to register surfing as an official religion.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Carroll|first1=Nick|title=Robert \"Nat\" Young (November 14, 1947-)|url=http://www.surfline.com/surfing-a-to-z/robert-nat-young-biography-and-photos_951/|website=Surfline|publisher=Surfline/Wavetrak, Inc|accessdate=24 October 2014|date=October 2000}}</ref>\n\n== Z ==\n*[[Frieda Zamba]] (1965\u2013 ) (USA) Four time world women's surfing champion 1984-1986 and 1988.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Lists of sportspeople by sport|Surfers]]\n[[Category:Surfers]]\n", "name_user": "Richaldito", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_surfers"}
{"title_page": "Dirk Weetendorf", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name                = Dirk Weetendorf\n| fullname            = Dirk Weetendorf\n| birth_date          = {{birth date and age|df=yes|1972|10|1}}\n| birth_place         = [[Fehmarn|Burg auf Fehmarn]], [[West Germany]]\n| height              = 1.87 m\n| position            = [[Forward (association football)|Striker]]\n| youthyears1         = \n| youthclubs1         = SV Heringsdorf\n| youthyears2         = \n| youthclubs2         = TSV Heiligenhafen\n| youthyears3         = \n| youthclubs3         = SV Fehmarn\n| youthyears4         = \n| youthclubs4         = [[Oldenburger SV]]\n| years1              = {{0|0000}}\u20131996\n| clubs1              = [[TSV Pansdorf]]\n| caps1               = \n| goals1              = \n| years2              = 1996\u20131998\n| clubs2              = [[Hamburger SV]]\n| caps2               = 23\n| goals2              = 3\n| years3              = 1998\u20131999\n| clubs3              = [[SV Werder Bremen|Werder Bremen]]\n| caps3               = 7\n| goals3              = 0\n| years4              = 1999\u20132003\n| clubs4              = [[Eintracht Braunschweig]]\n| caps4               = 60\n| goals4              = 37\n| totalcaps           = 90\n| totalgoals          = 40\n| manageryears1       = 2003\u20132007\n| managerclubs1       = [[Eintracht Braunschweig]] (youth)\n| manageryears2       = 2009\u20132012\n| managerclubs2       = ATSV Stockelsdorf\n| club-update         = 1 January 2013\n}}\n'''Dirk Weetendorf''' (born 1 October 1972) is a German former professional [[Association football|footballer]], who played as a [[forward (association football)|striker]], and current manager.{{citation needed|date=February 2014}}\n\n==Career==\nWeetendorf was born in [[Fehmarn|Burg auf Fehmarn]]. Between 1996 and 1999 he played three seasons in the [[Bundesliga]] for [[Hamburger SV]] and [[SV Werder Bremen|Werder Bremen]], but did not become a regular starter at either club. In 1999, he moved to [[Regionalliga Nord]] side [[Eintracht Braunschweig]], where he became a prolific scorer and contributed significantly to the club's promotion to the [[2. Fu\u00dfball-Bundesliga|2. Bundesliga]] in 2002. However, constant injury problems forced Weetendorf to retire early from football just one year later.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.braunschweiger-zeitung.de/sport/eintracht/karriereende-fuer-dirk-weetendorf-id384916.html|title=Karriereende f\u00fcr Dirk Weetendorf|work=[[Braunschweiger Zeitung]]|accessdate=19 April 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Honours==\n* [[DFB-Pokal]]: [[1998\u201399 DFB-Pokal|1998\u201399]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{fussballdaten|weetendorfdirk}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Weetendorf, Dirk}}\n[[Category:1972 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Fehmarn]]\n[[Category:Footballers from Schleswig-Holstein]]\n[[Category:Association football forwards]]\n[[Category:German footballers]]\n[[Category:German football managers]]\n[[Category:Eintracht Braunschweig players]]\n[[Category:Hamburger SV players]]\n[[Category:SV Werder Bremen players]]\n[[Category:Bundesliga players]]\n[[Category:Eintracht Braunschweig non-playing staff]]\n\n\n{{Germany-footy-forward-1970s-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox football biography\n| name                = Dirk Weetendorf\n| fullname            = Dirk Weetendorf\n| birth_date          = {{birth date and age|df=yes|1972|10|1}}\n| birth_place         = [[Fehmarn|Burg auf Fehmarn]], [[Germany]]\n| height              = {{Height|m=1.87}}\n| position            = [[Forward (association football)|Striker]]\n| youthyears1         = \n| youthclubs1         = SV Heringsdorf\n| youthyears2         = \n| youthclubs2         = TSV Heiligenhafen\n| youthyears3         = \n| youthclubs3         = SV Fehmarn\n| youthyears4         = \n| youthclubs4         = [[Oldenburger SV]]\n| years1              = {{0|0000}}\u20131996\n| clubs1              = [[TSV Pansdorf]]\n| caps1               = \n| goals1              = \n| years2              = 1996\u20131998\n| clubs2              = [[Hamburger SV]]\n| caps2               = 23\n| goals2              = 3\n| years3              = 1998\u20131999\n| clubs3              = [[SV Werder Bremen]]\n| caps3               = 7\n| goals3              = 0\n| years4              = 1999\u20132003\n| clubs4              = [[Eintracht Braunschweig]]\n| caps4               = 60\n| goals4              = 37\n| totalcaps           = 90\n| totalgoals          = 40\n| manageryears1       = 2003\u20132007\n| managerclubs1       = [[Eintracht Braunschweig]] (youth)\n| manageryears2       = 2009\u20132012\n| managerclubs2       = ATSV Stockelsdorf\n| club-update         = 1 January 2013\n}}\n'''Dirk Weetendorf''' (born 1 October 1972 in [[Fehmarn|Burg auf Fehmarn]]) is a retired German [[Association football|footballer]] and current manager.{{citation needed|date=February 2014}}\n\n==Career==\n\nBetween 1996 and 1999 Weetendorf played 3 seasons in the [[Fu\u00dfball-Bundesliga|Bundesliga]] for [[Hamburger SV]] and [[Werder Bremen]], but didn't become a regular starter at either club. In 1999, he moved to [[Regionalliga Nord]] side [[Eintracht Braunschweig]], where he became a prolific scorer and contributed significantly to the club's promotion to the [[2. Fu\u00dfball-Bundesliga|2. Bundesliga]] in 2002. However, constant injury problems forced Weetendorf to retire early from football just one year later.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.braunschweiger-zeitung.de/sport/eintracht/karriereende-fuer-dirk-weetendorf-id384916.html|title=Karriereende f\u00fcr Dirk Weetendorf|work=[[Braunschweiger Zeitung]]|accessdate=19 April 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Honours==\n* [[DFB-Pokal]] winner: [[1998\u201399 DFB-Pokal|1998\u201399]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{fussballdaten|weetendorfdirk}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Weetendorf, Dirk}}\n[[Category:1972 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]