://www.open-std.org/jtc1/sc22/wg21/ JTC1/SC22/WG21]{{snd}} the ISO/IEC C++ Standard Working Group\n* [https://isocpp.org/ Standard C++ Foundation]{{snd}} a non-profit organization that promotes the use and understanding of standard C++. Bjarne Stroustrup is a director of the organization.\n\n{{ISO standards}}\n{{Programming languages}}\n{{C++ programming language}}\n{{List of International Electrotechnical Commission standards}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:C}}\n[[Category:Algol programming language family]]\n[[Category:C++| ]]\n[[Category:C++ programming language family]]\n[[Category:Class-based programming languages]]\n[[Category:Cross-platform software]]\n[[Category:High-level programming languages]]\n[[Category:Object-oriented programming languages]]\n[[Category:Programming languages created in 1983]]\n[[Category:Programming languages with an ISO standard]]\n[[Category:Statically typed programming languages]]\n", "name_user": "Mauryaam8820", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(C++ program)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/C%2B%2B"}
{"title_page": "Bobirwa", "text_new": "{{Infobox settlement\n<!-- See Template:Infobox settlement for additional fields and descriptions -->\n| name                    = Bobirwa\n| native_name             =\n| native_name_lang        = <!-- ISO 639-2 code e.g. \"fr\" for French. If more than one, use {{lang}} instead -->\n| settlement_type         = Sub-district\n| image_skyline           =\n| image_alt               =\n| image_caption           =\n| image_flag              =\n| flag_alt                =\n| image_seal              =\n| seal_alt                =\n| image_shield            =\n| shield_alt              =\n| nickname                =\n| motto                   =\n| image_map               =\n| map_alt                 =\n| map_caption             =\n| pushpin_map             = Botswana\n| pushpin_label_position  =\n| pushpin_map_alt         =\n| pushpin_map_caption     =\n| coordinates             = {{coord|-21.97043|28.423335|display=inline,title}}\n| coor_pinpoint           =\n| coordinates_footnotes   =\n| subdivision_type        = Country\n| subdivision_name        = Botswana\n| subdivision_type1       = District\n| subdivision_name1       = [[Central District (Botswana)|Central District]]\n| subdivision_type2       = \n| subdivision_name2       =\n| subdivision_type3       =\n| subdivision_name3       =\n| leader_title            =\n| leader_name             =\n| area_total_km2          = \n| length_km               =\n| width_km                =\n| elevation_m             =\n| population_total        = \n| population_as_of        = \n| population_density_km2  = auto\n| population_note         = \n| timezone1               =\n| utc_offset1             =\n| timezone1_DST           =\n| utc_offset1_DST         =\n| postal_code_type        =\n| postal_code             =\n| area_code_type          =\n| area_code               =\n| iso_code                =\n| website                 = <!-- {{URL|example.com}} -->\n| footnotes               =\n}}\n\n'''Bobirwa''' Subdistrict is a jurisdiction in [[Botswana]]. It is populated by the Babirwa (Ba-Birwa) people who came from [[Transvaal (province)|Transvaal]] in present-day [[South Africa]]. \n\n[[Northern Sotho language|Sebirwa]] or [[Birwa]], the language spoken by the Babirwa people, is a dialect of [[Northern Sotho]], along with Bididi, Lobedu, Kgaga, Hananwa, [[Pedi]], Phalaborwa, Pulana, Tshwapong, Kutswe, Phahladira, Pai, Kopa, Kubu, etc. [[Northern Sotho]] is one of three Sesotho subgroups of [[Basotho]]. The two others are Western Sotho (better known as Setswana, which is largely spoken in [[Botswana]]), [[North West Province]], a small number of people in Matebeland Province of [[Zimbabwe]] and Southern Sotho (spoken in [[Lesotho]], [[Free State (province)|Free State]], and Vaal). The Basotho came from [[Cornelia, Free State|Ntswanatsatsi]].\n\n== History ==\nBefore [[Moshoeshoe]] and his Basotho nation of Lesotho, [[Basotho]] people were there. Moshoshoe didn't found  Basotho but he founded a nation   made up of Sesotho speaking people from different Sesotho speaking clans in which the British imperialist in Southern Africa errenous called Basotho nation, [[Lesotho]] cutting them off from the rest of other Basothos outside Lesotho in [[Orange Free State]] and [[Transvaal Province|Transvaal]] in present day [[South Africa]], [[Botswana]], [[Zimbabwe]], [[Namibia]] and [[Zambia]] as if Moshoshoe and his people were unique from other Basotho people. Basotho people were there before [[Moshoshoe]] the son of Mokhachane of another Basotho clan of Bamokoteli clan united the smaller and weaker clans of Basothos under his [[Bakwena]] clan leadership during Shaka's war of difaqane. Moshoshoe and his Bakwena clan and the rest of the other Basotho clan originates from Ntswanatsatsi in present day [[South Africa]]. Families moved away from each other in Ntswanatsatsi and started clans using a totem as symbol of their clan (like crocodile (Kwena) which Moshoshoe' ancestors used) and different families moved to different directions within the precolonial South Africa under different leadership. Under different leadership some settled in the Western side, present day [[North West Province]] others spread around Ntswanatsatsi to the present day [Free State]] and Lesotho, others to present day [[Botswana]] others to present day [[Zimbabwe]] and [[Zambia]], [[Namibia]] others  others moved  to the present day [[Gauteng]] in South Africa and they became patriarchs of the founding fathers of [[Bakgatla]] which also gave birth to [Northern Basotho]]  which in turn gave birth to different Northern clans with their dialects like [[BaPedi]] , Batlokwa,Babirwa, etc and others ended up in intermarriage with other tribes they moved next to and mingled with like Swatis, Vendas and Tsongas and Ngunis and in some places these Northern Basotho' Sotho was diluted by the influence of these tribe they found in the area, they moved into and lived alongside. This is what happened to a subgroup of Northern Basotho who end up becoming [[Mapulana]] with their Sesotho influenced by [[Swati]]. Also some of the Northern Basotho having a common denominator of \"apa\" (meaning talk) with Vendas, I mean Balovedu, BaGubu and [[Babirwa]] of [[Bobirwa]] in the Southern part of [[Botswana]] near the Zimbabwean border along the  Shashe river and with its dialect spoken on the other side of the border of Botswana in Zimbabwe.\n\nAfter the scattering of the Basothos from their cradle, different Basotho dialects from different locations within South Africa emerged and the Babirwa  people were one of those who emerged, coming out of Nareng in Letswalo area near [[Phalaborwa]] under the leadership of Tshukudu between 1510 and 1599. Babirwa moved from Nareng under their chief, They trekked further North and settled in Blauwberg in present-day [[Limpopo Province]]. Others remained in Blauwberg, living in surrounding areas such as [[Senwabarwana]]. Others who left Transvaal ended up in the southern part of present-day [[Zimbabwe]] near a place called [[Gwanda]] district in [[Matebeleland]] South. Gwanda was inhabited by Jahunda ([[Kalanga  dialect]]) speaking people and a group of Ndebele who moved southward from the Northern side of precolonial [[Matabeleland province]] which they invaded under their leader Mzilikazi who was forced by the Boers to leave Transvaal after running away from [[Shaka]] in [[Natal]] Other group of Babirwa left Bobirwa and joined their relatives who left Transvaal for Southern Zimbabwe when they left for Bobirwa.  \n\nNot all of Sothos of Zimbabwe are of Babirwa descent. The Babirwa from Zimbabwe are found in Gungwe, Ntalale, Tlhakadiyawa, Kafusi, Mawaza, Mafukung and surrounding villages. They are two types of Basotho in Zimbabwe, the Babirwa and the other Basothos who left Transvaal around the 1890s and early 1900 because they were displaced by the Boers and most of those Basothos came from Polokwane area, places like Moletse, Potgieterrus. Other Zimbabwean Sothos got [[Venda people|Venda]] and Tsonga  roots from [[Northern Transvaal]] present-day [[Limpopo Province]]. The Sotho of Zimbabwe which is similar to the Sesotho that is spoken in Messina and surrounding area is a corrupted [[Kubu language|Kubu]] and it is similar to Selobedu. From the above, it is clear that the Babirwa people also lived along the confluence of the Limpopo River and the [[Shashi River]], the area that today includes the Mapungubjwe Ruins. \n\nThe Babirwa in South Africa reside in areas north of the Bochum area, north of Polokwane. There are more than 40 Babirwa surnames in South Africa which include Sebone, Malema, Makhura, Makwati, Makhurane, Maphala, Nare, Tau, Tlou-Serope, [[Choshi]], Mmamadi, [[Legong]] (Lehong), Mangale, Taueatswala, Molefe, Mogano, Jibula (Tjibula) (Muhanu), [[Machete]], Lehomo, Raphahlelo, Raseokgo (Sebola), Phooko, Ramalepe, Boikanyo, Selema,  Morerwa (Murerwa) Makgatho, Maruatona, Monekwe (Monengwe), Madema Morebeng (Phosa) and many more. The word Bobirwa, therefore, means the land of (Babirwa) Ba-Birwa people.{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2013}}\n\nA large number of Babirwa left the northern South African shore and ended up living in what is today called the Bobirwa Sub District which is an administrative region in eastern [[Botswana]], part of the [[Central District (Botswana)|Central District]].\n[[Bobonong]] is the largest town and the headquarters of the sub-district. The sub-district is bounded by [[Zimbabwe]] to the northeast and [[South Africa]] to the southeast. The [[Limpopo River]] forms the boundary with South Africa.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.fao.org/3/y5744e/y5744e07.htm|title=Drought impact mitigation and prevention in the Limpopo River Basin|website=www.fao.org|access-date=2019-08-06}}</ref>\n\nThe Bobirwa Sub-district has an average annual rainfall of {{convert|300|to|400|mm}}. Soils are mainly loams to sandy clay loams. Bobirwa is the lowest part of Botswana, varying from {{convert|590|to|886|m}} above sea level. It is intersected by a network of channels that drain into the Limpopo. Villages include [[Mathathane]], [[Motlhabaneng]], [[Tsetsebjwe]], Kobojango, [[Bobonong]], [[Molalatau]], [[Tobane]], [[Mabolwe]], Semolale, [[Lepokole]], Zanzibar, Moletemane, [[Sefophe]] and Lentswelemoriti.{{sfn|Botswana College of Agriculture|2004|pp=5-7}}\n\nThe sub-district has been heavily degraded by agricultural activities and is susceptible to drought. Large areas in and around the villages are bare earth caused by clearing grasses to keep snakes and insects away. Overgrazing by sheep, goats, donkeys, and cattle is also another cause.{{sfn|Botswana College of Agriculture|2004|pp=5-7}} A study showed a substantial reduction in natural land cover between 1970 and 2010, combined with a significant increase in population.{{sfn|Botswana College of Agriculture|2004|pp=9-10}}\n\nIn addition to livestock, the sub-district is home to abundant wildlife. In 2000, there was a herd of around 200 elephants.{{sfn|Botswana College of Agriculture|2004|p=12}}\n\nIn 2011, it was reported that the government had approved the establishment of service centers in Tsetsebjwe, Mathathane, and Gobojango as well as other large infrastructure development projects such as road improvements, bridges, and electrification. This followed rapid economic growth in the previous three years. The local people could now shop and bank in Bobonong, rather than having to travel to [[Selebi-Phikwe]]. The new centers were expected to further improve access to services.{{sfn|Modikwa|2009}}\n\nIn 2012, there was a sharp increase in stock theft. This may have been caused by drought, which was forcing livestock to travel long distances to find grazing and water making them vulnerable to rustlers.{{sfn|Mazwiduma|2012}}\n\n==References==\n'''Citations'''\n{{reflist |colwidth=30em}}\n'''Sources'''\n{{refbegin}}\n*{{cite web\n |ref=harv\n |url=http://portal.unesco.org/ci/fr/files/18416/11117683861pilotproject_landcover_FinalReport.doc/pilotproject_landcover_FinalReport.doc\n |title=BOTSWANA REPORT Contract No. 4500010375\n |work=UNESCO Crosscutting Project\n |author=Botswana College of Agriculture\n |date=4 August 2004\n |accessdate=2012-09-17\n |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160104180221/http://portal.unesco.org/ci/fr/files/18416/11117683861pilotproject_landcover_FinalReport.doc/pilotproject_landcover_FinalReport.doc\n |archive-date=4 January 2016\n |url-status=dead\n }}\n*{{cite web |ref=harv |url=http://www.mmegi.bw/index.php?sid=1&aid=876&dir=2012/June/Friday8\n |work=Mmegi\n |title=Stocktheft on the rise in Bobirwa\n |last=Mazwiduma|first=Takongwa |date=8 June 2012\n |accessdate=2012-09-17}}\n*{{cite journal |ref=harv |url=http://www.mmegi.bw/index.php?sid=1&aid=12&dir=2009/January/Friday9\n |work=Mmegi\n |title=Massive infrastructural projects underway in Bobirwa\n |last=Modikwa |first=Onalenna |date=9 January 2009\n |accessdate=2012-09-17}} \n{{refend}}\n\n[[Category:Populated places in Botswana]]\n[[Category:Central District (Botswana)]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox settlement\n<!-- See Template:Infobox settlement for additional fields and descriptions -->\n| name                    = Bobirwa\n| native_name             =\n| native_name_lang        = <!-- ISO 639-2 code e.g. \"fr\" for French. If more than one, use {{lang}} instead -->\n| settlement_type         = Sub-district\n| image_skyline           =\n| image_alt               =\n| image_caption           =\n| image_flag              =\n| flag_alt                =\n| image_seal              =\n| seal_alt                =\n| image_shield            =\n| shield_alt              =\n| nickname                =\n| motto                   =\n| image_map               =\n| map_alt                 =\n| map_caption             =\n| pushpin_map             = Botswana\n| pushpin_label_position  =\n| pushpin_map_alt         =\n| pushpin_map_caption     =\n| coordinates             = {{coord|-21.97043|28.423335|display=inline,title}}\n| coor_pinpoint           =\n| coordinates_footnotes   =\n| subdivision_type        = Country\n| subdivision_name        = Botswana\n| subdivision_type1       = District\n| subdivision_name1       = [[Central District (Botswana)|Central District]]\n| subdivision_type2       = \n| subdivision_name2       =\n| subdivision_type3       =\n| subdivision_name3       =\n| leader_title            =\n| leader_name             =\n| area_total_km2          = \n| length_km               =\n| width_km                =\n| elevation_m             =\n| population_total        = \n| population_as_of        = \n| population_density_km2  = auto\n| population_note         = \n| timezone1               =\n| utc_offset1             =\n| timezone1_DST           =\n| utc_offset1_DST         =\n| postal_code_type        =\n| postal_code             =\n| area_code_type          =\n| area_code               =\n| iso_code                =\n| website                 = <!-- {{URL|example.com}} -->\n| footnotes               =\n}}\n\n'''Bobirwa''' Subdistrict is a jurisdiction in [[Botswana]]. It is populated by the Babirwa (Ba-Birwa) people who came from [[Transvaal (province)|Transvaal]] in present-day [[South Africa]]. \n\n[[Northern Sotho language|Sebirwa]] or [[Birwa]], the language spoken by the Babirwa people, is a dialect of [[Northern Sotho]], along with Bididi, Lobedu, Kgaga, Hananwa, [[Pedi]], Phalaborwa, Pulana, Tshwapong, Kutswe, Phahladira, Pai, Kopa, Kubu, etc. [[Northern Sotho]] is one of three Sesotho subgroups of [[Basotho]]. The two others are Western Sotho (better known as Setswana, which is largely spoken in [[Botswana]]), [[North West Province]], a small number of people in Matebeland Province of [[Zimbabwe]] and Southern Sotho (spoken in [[Lesotho]], [[Free State (province)|Free State]], and Vaal). The Basotho came from [[Cornelia, Free State|Ntswanatsatsi]].\n\n== History ==\nBefore [[Moshoeshoe]] and his Basotho nation of Lesotho, [[Basotho]] people were there. Moshoshoe didn't found  Basotho but he founded a nation   made up of Sesotho speaking people from different Sesotho speaking clans in which the British imperialist in Southern Africa errenous called Basotho nation, [[Lesotho]] cutting them off from the rest of other Basothos outside Lesotho in [[Orange Free State]] and [[Transvaal]] in present day [[South Africa]], [[Botswana]], [[Zimbabwe]], [[Namibia]] and [[Zambia]] as if Moshoshoe and his people were unique from other Basotho people. Basotho people were there before [[Moshoshoe]] the son of Mokhachane of another Basotho clan of Bamokoteli clan united the smaller and weaker clans of Basothos under his [[Bakwena]] clan leadership during Shaka's war of difaqane. Moshoshoe and his Bakwena clan and the rest of the other Basotho clan originates from Ntswanatsatsi in present day [[South Africa]]. Families moved away from each other in Ntswanatsatsi and started clans using a totem as symbol of their clan (like crocodile (Kwena) which Moshoshoe' ancestors used) and different families moved to different directions within the precolonial South Africa under different leadership. Under different leadership some settled in the Western side, present day [[North West Province]] others spread around Ntswanatsatsi to the present day [Free State]] and Lesotho, others to present day [[Botswana]] others to present day [[Zimbabwe]] and [[Zambia]], [[Namibia]] others  others moved  to the present day [[Gauteng]] in South Africa and they became patriarchs of the founding fathers of [[Bakgatla]] which also gave birth to [Northern Basotho]]  which in turn gave birth to different Northern clans with their dialects like [[BaPedi]] , Batlokwa,Babirwa, etc and others ended up in intermarriage with other tribes they moved next to and mingled with like Swatis, Vendas and Tsongas and Ngunis and in some places these Northern Basotho' Sotho was diluted by the influence of these tribe they found in the area, they moved into and lived alongside. This is what happened to a subgroup of Northern Basotho who end up becoming [[Mapulana]] with their Sesotho influenced by [[Swati]]. Also some of the Northern Basotho having a common denominator of \"apa\" (meaning talk) with Vendas, I mean Balovedu, BaGubu and [[Babirwa]] of [[Bobirwa]] in the Southern part of [[Botswana]] near the Zimbabwean border along the  Shashe river and with its dialect spoken on the other side of the border of Botswana in Zimbabwe.\n\nAfter the scattering of the Basothos from their cradle, different Basotho dialects from different locations within South Africa emerged and the Babirwa  people were one of those who emerged, coming out of Nareng in Letswalo area near [[Phalaborwa]] under the leadership of Tshukudu between 1510 and 1599. Babirwa moved from Nareng under their chief, They trekked further North and settled in Blauwberg in present-day [[Limpopo Province]]. Others remained in Blauwberg, living in surrounding areas such as [[Senwabarwana]]. Others who left Transvaal ended up in the southern part of present-day [[Zimbabwe]] near a place called [[Gwanda]] district in [[Matebeleland]] South. Gwanda was inhabited by Jahunda ([[Kalanga  dialect]]) speaking people and a group of Ndebele who moved southward from the Northern side of precolonial [[Matabeleland province]] which they invaded under their leader Mzilikazi who was forced by the Boers to leave Transvaal after running away from [[Shaka]] in [[Natal]] Other group of Babirwa left Bobirwa and joined their relatives who left Transvaal for Southern Zimbabwe when they left for Bobirwa.  \n\nNot all of Sothos of Zimbabwe are of Babirwa descent. The Babirwa from Zimbabwe are found in Gungwe, Ntalale, Tlhakadiyawa, Kafusi, Mawaza, Mafukung and surrounding villages. They are two types of Basotho in Zimbabwe, the Babirwa and the other Basothos who left Transvaal around the 1890s and early 1900 because they were displaced by the Boers and most of those Basothos came from Polokwane area, places like Moletse, Potgieterrus. Other Zimbabwean Sothos got [[Venda people|Venda]] and Tsonga  roots from [[Northern Transvaal]] present-day [[Limpopo Province]]. The Sotho of Zimbabwe which is similar to the Sesotho that is spoken in Messina and surrounding area is a corrupted [[Kubu language|Kubu]] and it is similar to Selobedu. From the above, it is clear that the Babirwa people also lived along the confluence of the Limpopo River and the [[Shashi River]], the area that today includes the Mapungubjwe Ruins. \n\nThe Babirwa in South Africa reside in areas north of the Bochum area, north of Polokwane. There are more than 40 Babirwa surnames in South Africa which include Sebone, Malema, Makhura, Makwati, Makhurane, Maphala, Nare, Tau, Tlou-Serope, [[Choshi]], Mmamadi, [[Legong]] (Lehong), Mangale, Taueatswala, Molefe, Mogano, Jibula (Tjibula) (Muhanu), [[Machete]], Lehomo, Raphahlelo, Raseokgo (Sebola), Phooko, Ramalepe, Boikanyo, Selema,  Morerwa (Murerwa) Makgatho, Maruatona, Monekwe (Monengwe), Madema Morebeng (Phosa) and many more. The word Bobirwa, therefore, means the land of (Babirwa) Ba-Birwa people.{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2013}}\n\nA large number of Babirwa left the northern South African shore and ended up living in what is today called the Bobirwa Sub District which is an administrative region in eastern [[Botswana]], part of the [[Central District (Botswana)|Central District]].\n[[Bobonong]] is the largest town and the headquarters of the sub-district. The sub-district is bounded by [[Zimbabwe]] to the northeast and [[South Africa]] to the southeast. The [[Limpopo River]] forms the boundary with South Africa.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.fao.org/3/y5744e/y5744e07.htm|title=Drought impact mitigation and prevention in the Limpopo River Basin|website=www.fao.org|access-date=2019-08-06}}</ref>\n\nThe Bobirwa Sub-district has an average annual rainfall of {{convert|300|to|400|mm}}. Soils are mainly loams to sandy clay loams. Bobirwa is the lowest part of Botswana, varying from {{convert|590|to|886|m}} above sea level. It is intersected by a network of channels that drain into the Limpopo. Villages include [[Mathathane]], [[Motlhabaneng]], [[Tsetsebjwe]], Kobojango, [[Bobonong]], [[Molalatau]], [[Tobane]], [[Mabolwe]], Semolale, [[Lepokole]], Zanzibar, Moletemane, [[Sefophe]] and Lentswelemoriti.{{sfn|Botswana College of Agriculture|2004|pp=5-7}}\n\nThe sub-district has been heavily degraded by agricultural activities and is susceptible to drought. Large areas in and around the villages are bare earth caused by clearing grasses to keep snakes and insects away. Overgrazing by sheep, goats, donkeys, and cattle is also another cause.{{sfn|Botswana College of Agriculture|2004|pp=5-7}} A study showed a substantial reduction in natural land cover between 1970 and 2010, combined with a significant increase in population.{{sfn|Botswana College of Agriculture|2004|pp=9-10}}\n\nIn addition to livestock, the sub-district is home to abundant wildlife. In 2000, there was a herd of around 200 elephants.{{sfn|Botswana College of Agriculture|2004|p=12}}\n\nIn 2011, it was reported that the government had approved the establishment of service centers in Tsetsebjwe, Mathathane, and Gobojango as well as other large infrastructure development projects such as road improvements, bridges, and electrification. This followed rapid economic growth in the previous three years. The local people could now shop and bank in Bobonong, rather than having to travel to [[Selebi-Phikwe]]. The new centers were expected to further improve access to services.{{sfn|Modikwa|2009}}\n\nIn 2012, there was a sharp increase in stock theft. This may have been caused by drought, which was forcing livestock to travel long distances to find grazing and water making them vulnerable to rustlers.{{sfn|Mazwiduma|2012}}\n\n==References==\n'''Citations'''\n{{reflist |colwidth=30em}}\n'''Sources'''\n{{refbegin}}\n*{{cite web\n |ref=harv\n |url=http://portal.unesco.org/ci/fr/files/18416/11117683861pilotproject_landcover_FinalReport.doc/pilotproject_landcover_FinalReport.doc\n |title=BOTSWANA REPORT Contract No. 4500010375\n |work=UNESCO Crosscutting Project\n |author=Botswana College of Agriculture\n |date=4 August 2004\n |accessdate=2012-09-17\n |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160104180221/http://portal.unesco.org/ci/fr/files/18416/11117683861pilotproject_landcover_FinalReport.doc/pilotproject_landcover_FinalReport.doc\n |archive-date=4 January 2016\n |url-status=dead\n }}\n*{{cite web |ref=harv |url=http://www.mmegi.bw/index.php?sid=1&aid=876&dir=2012/June/Friday8\n |work=Mmegi\n |title=Stocktheft on the rise in Bobirwa\n |last=Mazwiduma|first=Takongwa |date=8 June 2012\n |accessdate=2012-09-17}}\n*{{cite journal |ref=harv |url=http://www.mmegi.bw/index.php?sid=1&aid=12&dir=2009/January/Friday9\n |work=Mmegi\n |title=Massive infrastructural projects underway in Bobirwa\n |last=Modikwa |first=Onalenna |date=9 January 2009\n |accessdate=2012-09-17}} \n{{refend}}\n\n[[Category:Populated places in Botswana]]\n[[Category:Central District (Botswana)]]\n", "name_user": "Rodw", "label": "safe", "comment": "Disambiguating links toTransvaal(link changed toTransvaal Province) usingDisamAssist.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bobirwa"}
{"title_page": "Curfews and lockdowns related to the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic", "text_new": "{{short description|Details of restrictions imposed due to COVID-19}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic sidebar|expanded=international}}\n\nThis list of '''COVID-19 related curfews and lockdowns''' shows worldwide [[curfew]]s and similar restrictions (known as [[stay-at-home order]]s, shelter-in-place orders, [[Shutdown (economics)|shutdowns]]/[[lockdown]]s) related to the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]] and established to prevent further spread of the [[severe acute respiratory syndrome coronavirus 2]] (SARS-CoV-2), which causes [[coronavirus disease 2019|COVID-19]].\n\nThe pandemic has resulted in the largest amount of shutdowns/lockdowns worldwide at the same time in [[history]].{{cn|date=April 2020}} Curfews and lockdowns between and within nations are of varying stringency.\n\n==Current lockdowns==\n<div style=\"float:left;\">{{2020 coronavirus quarantines outside Hubei}}</div>\n{{clear}}\n\n[[File:Joint inspection by police and army in Malaysia during MCO.jpg|thumb|220px|Joint inspection by the [[Royal Malaysia Police|police]] and [[Malaysian Army|army]] during the enhanced [[2020 Malaysia movement control order|movement control order]] in Malaysia.]]\n[[File:CRPF trooper during Curfew.png|thumb|Officer of the [[Central Armed Police Forces]] during national COVID-19 curfew in India.]]\n[[File:High Street and Curfew Tower, Cushendall, Co. Antrim - geograph.org.uk - 1381257.jpg|thumb|Empty street in Cushendall, [[Northern Ireland]]]]\n[[File:6954Baliuag enhanced community quarantine 37.jpg|thumb|2020 [[Curfew Pass]] in Baliuag, Phillippines.]]\n[[File:Mahane Yehuda Market closed in coronavirus outbreak.jpg|thumb|Mahane Yehuda Market in Jerusalem.]]\n[[File:Policemen wearing masks patrolling Wuhan Tianhe Airport during Wuhan coronavirus outbreak.jpg|thumb|Policemen wearing masks patrolling Wuhan Tianhe Airport during Wuhan coronavirus outbreak (22 January 2020)]]\n\n==Type of regulation by country==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable mw-collapsible mw-collapsed style=\"font-size:80%;\"\n|-\n! Country !! Main article !! Type of regulation !! Start date !! Expiry date{{efn|Curfews or lockdowns may be extended. The date listed for the lifting of ongoing restrictions is the latest reported date.}}!! References\n|-\n|{{ALB}} || ||nationwide curfew from 13:00 to 05:00 on Mondays to Saturdays<br>full lockdown on Sundays ||{{Date table sorting|March 13}} || || <ref>{{cite web|url=https://de.reuters.com/article/health-coronavirus-albania-curfew/albanians-begin-life-under-daily-curfew-as-coronavirus-cases-rise-idINL8N2BG91I|title=Albanians begin life under daily curfew as coronavirus cases rise|last=|first=|date=23 March 2020|website=Reuters|language=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n|-\n|{{DZA}} || ||curfew in the capital city from 19:00 to 07:00, full lockdown in [[Blida]]<br>curfew expanded to 15:00 to 07:00 in capital city and eight other provinces, 19:00 to 07:00 in most other provinces || {{Date table sorting|March 24}} || ||<ref>{{cite web|url=https://fr.reuters.com/article/healthcareSector/idUSL8N2BG8QU|title=Algeria imposes curfew in capital|last=|first=|date=23 March 2020|website=Reuters|language=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/health-coronavirus-algeria-idUSL8N2BS0OU|title=Algeria extends curfew as coronavirus cases rise|date=2020-04-04|work=Reuters|access-date=2020-04-12|language=en}}</ref>\n|-\n|{{ARG}} || ||nationwide lockdown || {{Date table sorting|March 20}} ||{{Date table sorting|April 26}} ||<ref>{{cite web |title=Argentina begins unprecedented nationwide lockdown |url=https://www.batimes.com.ar/news/argentina/president-fernandez-orders-nationwide-lockdown.phtml |website=Buenos Aires Times |accessdate=2 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Argentina braces 