\n* [[Currie Cup]] winner in 1993.\n* [[Super Rugby|Super 10]] winner in 1993.\n\n===South Africa national rugby union team===\n* 34 caps\n* 6 tries (30 points).\n* Caps by year : 4 in [[1994 in sports|1994]], 8 in [[1995 in sports|1995]], 11 in [[1996 in sports|1996]], 2 in [[1997 in sports|1997]], 4 in [[1999 in sports|1999]], 3 in [[2000 in sports|2000]], 2 in [[2001 in sports|2001]].\n\n===World Cup===\n* 1995 : World Champions, 4 caps, ([[Australia national rugby union team|Wallabies]], [[Samoa national rugby union team|Samoa]], [[France national rugby union team|France]], [[New Zealand national rugby union team|All Blacks]]).\n* 1999 : missed with an injury sustained against [[New Zealand national rugby union team|All Blacks]] in [[Dunedin]].\n\n===Other caps===\n* Springboks A International (in 1994).\n* Student international.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20131216155221/http://www.genslin.us/bokke/SARugby.html Springboks in 1996]\n*[http://statistics.scrum.com/rugby_stats_05.asp?ID=ZMU6 scrum.com statistics]\n\n{{South Africa Squad 1995 World Cup}}\n{{Portal bar|Sport}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Mulder, Japie}}\n[[Category:1969 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People convicted of attempted rape]]\n[[Category:People convicted of indecent assault]]\n[[Category:South African rugby union players]]\n[[Category:South Africa international rugby union players]]\n[[Category:Rugby union centres]]\n[[Category:Golden Lions players]]\n[[Category:Lions (Super Rugby) players]]\n", "name_user": "Rodw", "label": "safe", "comment": "Disambiguating links toTransvaal(link changed toTransvaal Province) usingDisamAssist.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Japie_Mulder"}
{"title_page": "Taurus (astrology)", "text_new": "{{short description|Second astrological sign in the present zodiac}}\n{{about|the astrological sign|the constellation|Taurus (constellation)}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date= July 2019}}\n{{Infobox zodiac\n| name       = Taurus \n| image    = Taurus by Johannes Hevelius.JPG\n| image symbol  = Taurus.svg\n| symbol        = [[Bull]]\n| nr            = 2\n| constellation = [[Taurus (constellation)|Taurus]]\n| element       = [[Earth sign|Earth]]\n| quality       = [[Fixed sign|Fixed]]\n| domicile      = [[Venus (astrology)|Venus]]\n| exaltation    = [[Moon (astrology)|Moon]]\n| fall          = Traditional: No planet is fall or depressed here; Modern: [[Uranus]]\n| detriment     = [[Mars]]\n}}\n{{Astrology}}\n\n'''Taurus''' ('''{{Emoji presentation|\u2649|text}}''') (Latin for [[bull]], derived from the   [[Ancient Greek|Greek]] word {{lang|grc|\u03a4\u03b1\u1fe6\u03c1\u03bf\u03c2}}) is the second [[astrological sign]] in the present [[zodiac]]. It spans from 30\u00b0 to 60\u00b0 of the zodiac. This sign belongs to the Earth element or triplicity, and has a feminine or negative polarity, as well as a Fixed modality, quality, or quadruplicity. It is a Venus-ruled sign like Libra. The Moon has its exaltation here at exactly 3\u00b0. The Sun transits this sign from approximately April 20 until May 21 in [[western astrology]].{{sfn|Oxford|2019}}\n\n==History==\n{{unreferenced|section|date=February 2020}}\nTaurus was the ''first sign'' of the zodiac established among the ancient [[Mesopotamia]]ns, who called it \"The Great Bull of Heaven\" as it was the constellation through which the Sun rose on the [[vernal equinox]] at that time.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=So\u0142tysiak|first=Arkadiusz|date=2001|title=The Bull of Heaven in Mesopotamian Sources|url=http://www.cultureandcosmos.org/pdfs/5/5-2-Soltysiak_Bull_of_Heaven.pdf|journal=Culture and Cosmos|volume=5|pages=3-21|via=}}</ref> Cults centered around [[sacred bull]]s began to form in Assyria, Egypt, and Crete during [[Astrological age|The Age of Taurus]], or \"The Age of Earth, Agriculture, and the Bull\".\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Works cited==\n*{{citation|publisher = US Naval Observatory | author = Astronomical Applications Department | title = Multiyear Computer Interactive Almanac | location = Washington DC | year = 2011 | version = 2.2.2. | mode = cs1 | ref=harv}} Longitude of Sun, apparent geocentric ecliptic of date, interpolated to find time of crossing 0\u00b0, 30\u00b0....\n*{{cite web| author = Astroroom | date = 2012 |url=http://www.astroroom.com/opposing-zodiac-signs.html|title=Opposing zodiac signs: themes of the six axes|website=astroroom.com | ref = harv}}\n*{{cite web|url=https://www.lexico.com/|author=Oxford University Press |title=Taurus, Gemini - definitions of Taurus and Gemini in English from Lexico.com |ref = {{harvid|Oxford|2019}}}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://warburg.sas.ac.uk/vpc/VPC_search/subcats.php?cat_1=9&cat_2=71&cat_3=32&cat_4=41&cat_5=43 Warburg Institute Iconographic Database (over 300 medieval and early modern images of Taurus)]\n\n{{Zodiac}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Taurus (Astrology)}}\n[[Category:Western astrological signs]]\n[[Category:Mythological bovines]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Second astrological sign in the present zodiac}}\n{{about|the astrological sign|the constellation|Taurus (constellation)}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date= July 2019}}\n{{Infobox zodiac\n| name       = Taurus \n| image    = Taurus by Johannes Hevelius.JPG\n| image symbol  = Taurus.svg\n| symbol        = [[Bull]]\n| nr            = 2\n| constellation = [[Taurus (constellation)|Taurus]]\n| element       = [[Earth sign|Earth]]\n| quality       = [[Fixed sign|Fixed]]\n| domicile      = [[Venus (astrology)|Venus]]\n| exaltation    = [[Moon (astrology)|Moon]]\n| fall          = Traditional: No planet is fall or depressed here; Modern: [[Uranus]]\n| detriment     = [[Mars]]\n}}\n{{Astrology}}\n\n'''Taurus''' ('''{{Emoji presentation|\u2649|text}}''') (Latin for [[bull]], derived from the   [[Ancient Greek|Greek]] word {{lang|grc|\u03a4\u03b1\u1fe6\u03c1\u03bf\u03c2}}) is the second [[astrological sign]] in the present [[zodiac]]. It spans from 30\u00b0 to 60\u00b0 of the zodiac. This sign belongs to the Earth element or triplicity, and has a feminine or negative polarity, as well as a Fixed modality, quality, or quadruplicity. It is a Venus-ruled sign like Libra. The Moon has its exaltation here at exactly 3\u00b0. The Sun transits this sign from approximately April 21 until May 21 in [[western astrology]].{{sfn|Oxford|2019}}\n\n==History==\n{{unreferenced|section|date=February 2020}}\nTaurus was the ''first sign'' of the zodiac established among the ancient [[Mesopotamia]]ns, who called it \"The Great Bull of Heaven\" as it was the constellation through which the Sun rose on the [[vernal equinox]] at that time.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=So\u0142tysiak|first=Arkadiusz|date=2001|title=The Bull of Heaven in Mesopotamian Sources|url=http://www.cultureandcosmos.org/pdfs/5/5-2-Soltysiak_Bull_of_Heaven.pdf|journal=Culture and Cosmos|volume=5|pages=3-21|via=}}</ref> Cults centered around [[sacred bull]]s began to form in Assyria, Egypt, and Crete during [[Astrological age|The Age of Taurus]], or \"The Age of Earth, Agriculture, and the Bull\".\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Works cited==\n*{{citation|publisher = US Naval Observatory | author = Astronomical Applications Department | title = Multiyear Computer Interactive Almanac | location = Washington DC | year = 2011 | version = 2.2.2. | mode = cs1 | ref=harv}} Longitude of Sun, apparent geocentric ecliptic of date, interpolated to find time of crossing 0\u00b0, 30\u00b0....\n*{{cite web| author = Astroroom | date = 2012 |url=http://www.astroroom.com/opposing-zodiac-signs.html|title=Opposing zodiac signs: themes of the six axes|website=astroroom.com | ref = harv}}\n*{{cite web|url=https://www.lexico.com/|author=Oxford University Press |title=Taurus, Gemini - definitions of Taurus and Gemini in English from Lexico.com |ref = {{harvid|Oxford|2019}}}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://warburg.sas.ac.uk/vpc/VPC_search/subcats.php?cat_1=9&cat_2=71&cat_3=32&cat_4=41&cat_5=43 Warburg Institute Iconographic Database (over 300 medieval and early modern images of Taurus)]\n\n{{Zodiac}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Taurus (Astrology)}}\n[[Category:Western astrological signs]]\n[[Category:Mythological bovines]]\n", "name_user": "2a00:23c4:1381:f01:3de9:9c85:be4d:5fb2", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(Fixed typo Taurus begins in April 20 th \ud83e\udd17)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Taurus_(astrology)"}
{"title_page": "Anne Schedeen", "text_new": "{{Infobox person\n| name          = Anne Schedeen\n| image         = Anne Schedeen (2019 crop).jpg\n| caption       = Schedeen with an ALF toy in 2019\n| birthname     = Luanne Ruth Schedeen\n| birth_date    = {{birth date and age|1949|1|8}} \n| birth_place   = [[Portland, Oregon|Portland]], [[Oregon]], U.S.\n| death_date    = \n| death_place   = \n| occupation    = Actress\n| yearsactive   = 1972&ndash;present\n| spouse        = {{marriage|Christopher Barrett|1982}}\n| children = 1\n}}\n\n'''Luanne Ruth Schedeen''' (born January 8, 1949), known professionally as '''Anne Schedeen''', is an American actress who worked primarily in television. She appeared in numerous guest-starring television roles in the 1970s before portraying the lead role of Kate Tanner on the series ''[[ALF (TV series)|ALF]]'' from 1986 until 1990.\n\nSchedeen began her career in 1974, appearing in small television roles, and was cast in a supporting part in the sci-fi horror film ''[[Embryo (1976 film)|Embryo]]'' (1976). She subsequently had recurring roles on ''[[Emergency!]]'' and ''[[Three's Company]]'' in the mid-to-late 1970s. In 1984, she was cast on the short-lived series ''[[Paper Dolls]]'' opposite [[Lloyd Bridges]] and [[Lauren Hutton]]. She appeared as Emily Phillips on the successful comedy series \u201cCheers\u201d (Season 2 episode 20), before appearing in all four seasons of ''ALF''. She later appeared in a recurring role on the series ''[[Judging Amy]]'' in 2001.\n\n==Early life==\n[[File:Anne Schedeen 1967 yearbook photo.png|thumb|upright=.5|right|Schedeen's junior yearbook photo]]\nLuanne Ruth Schedeen was born January 8, 1949 in [[Portland, Oregon]].<ref name=keen/> Her mother, Betty Jane (n\u00e9e Moore) was also a native of Portland.<ref name=keen>{{cite book|title=Rand Ramblings: From the arrival of Francis Rand, Strawbery Banke, NH, 1630, to the 90th birthday anniversary of Margaret Rand Keen, Topeka, KS, 1985|p=226|year=1985|author1=Keen, Ray Albert|author2=Keen, Dorothy|publisher=R. & D. Keen|oclc=608610411|location=Manhattan, Kansas}}</ref> Her father was Roland E. 'Poly' Schedeen, a farmer and former [[Oregon State Senate|Oregon State Senator]].<ref name=outlook/> Schedeen has two younger siblings: a sister, Sarabeth, and brother Tony; as well as one elder half-brother, Brinkley (1946\u20132009),<ref name=outlook>{{cite web|work=[[The Outlook (Gresham)|The Gresham Outlook]]|title=Obituaries: Brinkley James Schedeen|date=May 30, 2009|archive-url=https://archive.today/20190225040111/https://pamplinmedia.com/component/content/article?id=50331|archive-date=February 25, 2019|last=Hall|first=Calvin|url=https://pamplinmedia.com/component/content/article?id=50331|access-date=February 25, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> from her mother's first marriage.<ref name=keen/>\n\nSchedeen described herself as an introverted child: \"I was so introverted as a little girl I would hide under the skirts of the dining room table and just listen to the adults.\"<ref name=ss/> Due to her extreme shyness, Schedeen's mother enrolled her in youth drama classes to help her become \"more comfortable with the world.\"<ref name=ss/> She attended [[Gresham High School (Oregon)|Gresham High School]] in [[Gresham, Oregon]],<ref>{{cite book|year=1966|p=154|title=Munhinotu 1966|publisher=[[Gresham High School (Oregon)|Gresham High School]]}} (School yearbook).</ref> graduating in 1967. She subsequently relocated to [[New York City]] to pursue an acting career.\n\n==Career==\n===Early roles===\nIn New York, Schedeen signed an acting contract with [[Universal Pictures]],<ref name=wp>{{cite web|work=[[The Washington Post]]|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/archive/lifestyle/tv/1988/07/10/alfs-mom-enjoys-success-in-hit-series/f6aa5867-92d3-40eb-8c75-659f079548c9/|title=ALF's mom enjoys success in hit series|author=Buck, Jerry|date=July 10, 1988|archive-url=https://archive.today/20190225050038/https://www.washingtonpost.com/archive/lifestyle/tv/1988/07/10/alfs-mom-enjoys-success-in-hit-series/f6aa5867-92d3-40eb-8c75-659f079548c9/?noredirect=on|archive-date=February 25, 2019|access-date=February 25, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> and subsequently moved to Los Angeles.  From 1974 to 1976, Schedeen appeared in a recurring role as Carol in the series ''[[Emergency!]]'',<ref name=wp/> and guest-starred as doctor [[Marcus Welby]]'s daughter, Carol Porter, in 12 episodes of the medical drama ''[[Marcus Welby, M.D.]]''.<ref name=tvg/> In 1976, she was cast in a supporting part in the sci-fi horror film ''[[Embryo (1976 film)|Embryo]]'', co-starring with [[Rock Hudson]] and [[Diane Ladd]], in which she played the daughter-in-law of a doctor (Hudson) who uses growth hormones to begin growing humans.<ref>{{cite magazine|title=Review: ''Embryo''|work=[[Cinefantastique]]|volume=5|p=21|issn=0145-6032|date=1976|publisher=F.S. Clarke}}</ref>\n\nIn 1979, she had a supporting role in the television drama ''[[Champions: A Love Story]]'',<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bfi.org.uk/films-tv-people/4ce2b6fe8f6c9|work=[[British Film Institute]]|title=''Champions: A Love Story''|archive-url=https://archive.today/20190225050447/https://www.bfi.org.uk/films-tv-people/4ce2b6fe8f6c9|archive-date=February 25, 2019|access-date=February 25, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> and subsequently guest-starred on several episodes of the comedy series ''[[Three's Company]]'' from 1977 to 1982.<ref name=tvg/> Schedeen had a supporting role on the short-lived series ''[[Paper Dolls]]'' (1984),<ref name=ss/> co-starring with [[Lauren Hutton]] and [[Morgan Fairchild]].<ref name=tvg/>\n\n===''ALF'' and later work===\nSchedeen is best known for her role as Kate Tanner on the [[NBC]] sitcom ''[[ALF (TV series)|ALF]],''<ref>{{cite news|url=https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/sptimes/access/51350059.html?dids=51350059:51350059&FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:FT&type=current&date=Jul+31%2C+1988&author=JERRY+BUCK&pub=St.+Petersburg+Times&desc=The+recognition+factor+hits+home+for+Anne+Schedeen+of+%60ALF%27+Series%3A+COVER+STORY&pqatl=google|title=The recognition factor hits home for Anne Schedeen of `ALF' Series|date=July 31, 1988|work=[[Tampa Bay Times|St. Petersburg Times]]|quote=A man says, 'You're the woman on ALF.' I'd never been recognized before. The recognition came when the show started hitting the Top 10 in the ratings.\"|accessdate=June 16, 2011}}</ref> which ran from 1986 to 1990, and in which she portrayed a mother who takes an alien into her home. ''ALF'' was a commercial success, and brought Schedeen international attention.<ref name=wp/> After the series' conclusion, she appeared in ''[[Perry Mason (TV film series)|Perry Mason: The Case of the Maligned Mobster]]'' (1991), and in 2001 had a recurring guest-starring role on the legal drama series ''[[Judging Amy]]''.<ref name=tvg/>\n\n==Personal life==\nSchedeen met her husband, a talent agent named Christopher Barrett,<ref>{{cite news|work=[[Chicago Tribune]]|location=Chicago, Illinois|url=https://www.chicagotribune.com/news/ct-xpm-1989-01-05-8902220939-story.html|date=January 5, 1989|title='ALF' Will Get Babied a Little Bit|author=Elias, Thomas D.|archive-url=https://archive.today/20190225042548/https://www.chicagotribune.com/news/ct-xpm-1989-01-05-8902220939-story.html|archive-date=February 25, 2019|access-date=February 25, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> while the two appeared together in a stage play in 1972.<ref name=ss>{{cite news|url=https://www.sun-sentinel.com/news/fl-xpm-1988-06-26-8802060752-story.html|work=[[Sun-Sentinel]]|title=Actress enjoying status of stardom|date=June 26, 1988|archive-url=https://archive.today/20190225042034/https://www.sun-sentinel.com/news/fl-xpm-1988-06-26-8802060752-story.html|archive-date=February 25, 2019|location=Fort Lauderdale, Florida|author=DuBois, Stephanie|access-date=February 25, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> The two married in 1982 on the tenth anniversary of their first date.<ref name=ss/> The couple has a daughter, Taylor, born in 1991.\n\nIn 2015, Schedeen became an ambassador for [[Holiday Heroes]], a Bulgarian-based non-profit organization assisting disadvantaged families.<ref>{{cite web|work=[[MeTV]]|url=https://www.metv.com/lists/what-ever-happened-to-the-cast-of-alf|title=What ever happened to the cast of 'ALF'?|date=June 12, 2017|author=MeTV Staff|archive-url=https://archive.today/20190225045140/https://www.metv.com/lists/what-ever-happened-to-the-cast-of-alf|archive-date=February 25, 2019|access-date=February 25, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\n===Film===\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders sortable\" style=\"margin-right: 0;\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | Year\n! scope=\"col\" | Title\n! scope=\"col\" | Role\n! scope=\"col\" class=\"unsortable\" | Notes\n! scope=\"col\" class=\"unsortable\" | {{Tooltip|Ref.|Reference}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| 1974\n| ''Aloha Means Goodbye''\n| Stewardess\n| Television film\n| align=center|\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"|1975\n|''You Lie So Deep, My Love''\n| Ellen\n| Television film\n| align=center|\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| 1976\n| ''[[Embryo (1976 film)|Embryo]]''\n| Helen Holliston\n|\n| align=center|\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| 1977\n| '' Flight to Holocaust ''\n| Linda Michaels\n| Television film\n| align=center|\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| 1977\n| ''[[Exo-Man]]''\n| Emily Frost\n| Television film\n| align=center|\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| 1978\n| ''Almost Heaven''\n| Margie\n| Television film\n| align=center|\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| 1979\n| ''[[Champions: A Love Story]]''\n| Diane Kachatorian\n| Television film\n| align=center|\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"|1979\n| ''Never Say Never''\n| Dr. Sarah Keaton\n| Television film\n| align=center|\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| 1982\n| ''Little Darlings''\n| Camp Counselor\n| Television film\n| align=center|\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| 1983\n| ''[[Second Thoughts (1983 film)|Second Thoughts]]''\n| Janis\n|\n| align=center|<ref name=tvg/>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"|1985\n| ''[[Braker]]''\n| Lieutenant Polly Peters\n| Television film\n| a